Prosper Loan Data Exploration

Greg Clunies

3/18/2018

========================================================

Tip: One of the requirements of this project is that your code follows good formatting techniques, including limiting your lines to 80 characters or less. If you’re using RStudio, go into Preferences > Code > Display to set up a margin line to help you keep track of this guideline!

This report explores data on 113,937 Prosper loans, with 81 variables/attributes on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, borrower employment status, borrower credit history, and the latest payment information.

Prosper specializes is peer-to-peer lending, allowing everyday people to acquire and fund loans in amounts ranging from $2,000 to $35,000.

A description of each attribute in the loan dataset is provided here.

Based on the information provided in the attribute descriptions, certian attributes were only collected pre/post July 2009. To simplify the analysis, we will ony look at the loan dataa after July 2009. In other words, only data from August 2009 onwards will be explored.

Judging by the above histograms, we can see that the number of loans issued per day has groan substanially from 2010 to 2014. What is the current status of these loans over that time period?

Between July 2009 and the last update of this data (03/11/2014), 19501 Prosper loans had been completed, 56576 loans were currently issued, 997 loans were in default (extended period in which borrower has not paid), 5326 had been charged off (money owed, but creditor has given up on collecting = BAD DEBT), 2067 loans were past due, and 205 were in final processing.

Based on teh data, Prosper only provides loans at 12, 36, and 60 month terms.

As a starting point, having not being familiar Prosper and their service (for borrowers or investors) it would be interesting to get an idea of the typical rates for borrowers and estimated returns for investors.

It looks like most borrowers get a rate around 0.15 to 0.2 (median 0.1875), but we see a pretty that a substational amount of borrowers get rates around 0.26. Shockingly, we see that the most common rate for borrowers is 0.32 (32%)!

Estimated returns appear to follow a much more normal distrubution with a median estimated return of 0.09211 (9%). Although hard to distingusih at first, we can also see that some loans are actually estimated to lose money for their investors! Remind me to steer clear of these if I ever invest in Prosper loans. I wonder if there any common traits amongst loans that are estimated lo lose money? Let’s leave that question for later.
